# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sigma-delta-adc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] In digital signal processing, **downsampling**, **subsampling**, **compression**, and **decimation** are terms associated with the process of *resampling* in a multi-rate digital signal processing system.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Both *downsampling* and *decimation* can be synonymous with *compression*, or they can describe an entire process of bandwidth reduction (filtering) and sample-rate reduction.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] When the process is performed on a sequence of samples of a *signal* or a continuous function, it produces an approximation of the sequence that would have been obtained by sampling the signal at a lower rate (or density, as in the case of a photograph).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] *Decimate* the filtered signal by *M*; that is, keep only every *M*th sample.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Step 2 alone creates undesirable aliasing (i.e. high-frequency signal components will copy into the lower frequency band and be mistaken for lower frequencies).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Step 1, when necessary, suppresses aliasing to an acceptable level.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] In this application, the filter is called an anti-aliasing filter, and its design is discussed below.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Also see undersampling for information about decimating bandpass functions and signals.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] When the anti-aliasing filter is an IIR design, it relies on feedback from output to input, prior to the second step.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] With FIR filtering, it is an easy matter to compute only every *M*th output.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] where the *h*[•] sequence is the impulse response, and *K* is its length.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] *x*[•] represents the input sequence being downsampled.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] In a general purpose processor, after computing *y*[*n*], the easiest way to compute *y*[*n*+1] is to advance the starting index in the *x*[•] array by *M*, and recompute the dot product.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] In the case *M*=2, *h*[•] can be designed as a half-band filter, where almost half of the coefficients are zero and need not be included in the dot products.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Impulse response coefficients taken at intervals of *M* form a subsequence, and there are *M* such subsequences (phases) multiplexed together.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] The dot product is the sum of the dot products of each subsequence with the corresponding samples of the *x*[•] sequence.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Furthermore, because of downsampling by *M*, the stream of *x*[•] samples involved in any one of the *M* dot products is never involved in the other dot products.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Thus *M* low-order FIR filters are each filtering one of *M* multiplexed *phases* of the input stream, and the *M* outputs are being summed.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] This viewpoint offers a different implementation that might be advantageous in a multi-processor architecture.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] In other words, the input stream is demultiplexed and sent through a bank of M filters whose outputs are summed.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] When implemented that way, it is called a **polyphase** filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] The equivalence of this inefficient method and the implementation described above is known as the *first Noble identity*.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] It is sometimes used in derivations of the polyphase method.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Let *X*(*f*) be the Fourier transform of any function, *x*(*t*), whose samples at some interval, *T*, equal the *x*[*n*] sequence.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] When *T* has units of seconds, f has units of hertz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] The periodic summation has been reduced in amplitude and periodicity by a factor of *M*.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] An example of both these distributions is depicted in the two traces of Fig 1.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Aliasing occurs when adjacent copies of *X*(*f*) overlap.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] The purpose of the anti-aliasing filter is to ensure that the reduced periodicity does not create overlap.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] The condition that ensures the copies of *X*(*f*) do not overlap each other is: $B<{\tfrac {0.5}{T}}\cdot {\tfrac {1}{M}},$ so that is the maximum cutoff frequency of an *ideal* anti-aliasing filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Let *M/L* denote the decimation factor, where: M, L ∈ $\mathbb {Z}$ ; M > L.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Step 1 requires a lowpass filter after increasing (*expanding*) the data rate, and step 2 requires a lowpass filter before decimation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] Therefore, both operations can be accomplished by a single filter with the lower of the two cutoff frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/decimation-signal-processing] For the *M* > *L* case, the anti-aliasing filter cutoff, ${\tfrac {0.5}{M}}$ *cycles per intermediate sample*, is the lower frequency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Both ADCs and DACs can employ delta-sigma modulation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] A delta-sigma ADC (e.g., Figure 1 top) encodes an analog signal using high-frequency delta-sigma modulation and then applies a digital filter to demodulate it to a high-bit digital output at a lower sampling frequency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] A delta-sigma DAC (e.g., Figure 1 bottom) encodes a high-resolution digital input signal into a lower-resolution, but higher sample-frequency signal that may then be mapped to voltages and smoothed with an analog filter for demodulation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In both cases, the temporary use of a low bit depth signal at a higher sampling frequency simplifies circuit design and takes advantage of the efficiency and high accuracy in time of digital electronics.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Primarily because of its cost efficiency and reduced circuit complexity, this technique has found increasing use in modern electronic components such as DACs, ADCs, frequency synthesizers, switched-mode power supplies and motor controllers.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The coarsely-quantized output of a delta-sigma ADC is occasionally used directly in signal processing or as a representation for signal storage (e.g., Super Audio CD stores the raw output of a 1-bit delta-sigma modulator).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] While this article focuses on synchronous modulation, which requires a precise clock for quantization, asynchronous delta-sigma modulation instead runs without a clock.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] When transmitting an analog signal directly, all noise in the system and transmission is added to the analog signal, reducing its quality.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Digitizing it enables noise-free transmission, storage, and processing.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In Nyquist-rate ADCs, an analog signal is sampled at a relatively low sampling frequency just above its Nyquist rate (twice the signal's highest frequency) and quantized by a multi-level quantizer to produce a multi-bit digital signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Such higher-bit methods seek accuracy in amplitude directly, but require extremely precise components and so may suffer from poor linearity.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Oversampling converters instead produce a lower bit depth result at a much higher sampling frequency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Another key aspect given by oversampling is the frequency/resolution tradeoff.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The decimation filter put after the modulator not only filters the whole sampled signal in the band of interest (cutting the noise at higher frequencies), but also reduces the sampling rate, and hence the representable frequency range, of the signal, while increasing the sample amplitude resolution.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This improvement in amplitude resolution is obtained by a sort of *averaging* of the higher-data-rate bitstream.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta modulation is an earlier related low-bit oversampling method that also uses negative feedback, but only encodes the derivative of the signal (its *delta*) rather than its amplitude.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The result is a stream of marks and spaces representing up or down movement of the signal, which must be integrated to reconstruct the signal's amplitude.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The differentiation alters the signal's spectrum by amplifying high-frequency noise, attenuating low-frequencies, and dropping the DC component.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This makes its dynamic range and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) inversely proportional to signal frequency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta modulation suffers from slope overload if signals move too fast.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] And it is susceptible to transmission disturbances that result in cumulative error.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Delta-sigma modulation rearranges the integrator and quantizer of a delta modulator so that the output carries information corresponding to the amplitude of the input signal instead of just its derivative.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This also has the benefit of incorporating desirable noise shaping into the conversion process, to deliberately move quantization noise to frequencies higher than the signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In the specific case of a single-bit synchronous ΔΣ ADC, an analog voltage signal is effectively converted into a pulse frequency, or pulse density, which can be understood as pulse-density modulation (PDM).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] A sequence of positive and negative pulses, representing bits at a known fixed rate, is very easy to generate, transmit, and accurately regenerate at the receiver, given only that the timing and sign of the pulses can be recovered.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Given such a sequence of pulses from a delta-sigma modulator, the original waveform can be reconstructed with adequate precision.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The use of PDM as a signal representation is an alternative to PCM.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Alternatively, the high-frequency PDM can later be downsampled through decimation and requantized to convert it into a multi-bit PCM code at a lower sampling frequency closer to the Nyquist rate of the frequency band of interest.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The seminal paper combining feedback with oversampling to achieve delta modulation was by F. de Jager of Philips Research Laboratories in 1952.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The principle of improving the resolution of a coarse quantizer by use of feedback, which is the basic principle of delta-sigma conversion, was first described in a 1954-filed patent by C.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It was not named as such until a 1962 paper by Inose et al. of University of Tokyo, which came up with the idea of adding a filter in the forward path of the delta modulator.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] However, Charles B Brahm of United Aircraft Corp in 1961 filed a patent "Feedback integrating system" with a feedback loop containing an integrator with multi-bit quantization shown in its Fig 1.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Wooley's "The Evolution of Oversampling Analog-to-Digital Converters" gives more history and references to relevant patents.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Some avenues of variation (which may be applied in different combinations) are the modulator's order, the quantizer's bit depth, the manner of decimation, and the oversampling ratio.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Noise of the quantizer can be further shaped by replacing the quantizer itself with another ΔΣ modulator.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This creates a second-order modulator, which can be rearranged in a cascaded fashion (Figure 2).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This process can be repeated to increase the order even more.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] While first-order modulators are unconditionally stable, stability analysis must be performed for higher-order noise-feedback modulators.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The modulator can also be classified by the bit depth of its quantizer.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] A quantizer that distinguishes between *N-levels* is called a *log2N* bit quantizer.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] For example, a simple comparator has 2 levels and so is a 1-bit quantizer; a 3-level quantizer is called a *1.5* bit quantizer; a 4-level quantizer is a 2-bit quantizer; a 5-level quantizer is called a *2.5-bit* quantizer.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Higher bit quantizers inherently produce less quantization noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] One criticism of 1-bit quantization is that adequate amounts of dither cannot be used in the feedback loop, so distortion can be heard under some conditions (more discussion at Direct Stream Digital § DSD vs.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Many of the issues of 1-bit modulation can be treated by look-ahead sigma-delta modulation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Decimation is strongly associated with delta-sigma modulation, but is distinct and outside the scope of this article.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The original 1962 paper didn't describe decimation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Oversampled data in the early days was sent as is.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The proposal to decimate oversampled delta-sigma data using digital filtering before converting it into PCM audio was made by D.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Goodman at Bell Labs in 1969, to reduce the ΔΣ signal from its high sampling rate while increasing its bit depth.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Decimation may be done in a separate chip on the receiving end of the delta-sigma bit stream, sometimes by a dedicated module inside of a microcontroller, which is useful for interfacing with PDM MEMS microphones, though many ΔΣ ADC integrated circuits include decimation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Some microcontrollers even incorporate both the modulator and decimator.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Cascaded integrator–comb filters: These are called sincN filters, equivalent to cascading the above sinc1 filter N times and rearranging the order of operations for computational efficiency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Lower N filters are simpler, settle faster, and have less attenuation in the baseband, while higher N filters are slightly more complex and settle slower and have more droop in the passband, but better attenuate undesired high-frequency noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Compensation filters can, however, be applied to counteract undesired passband attenuation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] SincN filters are appropriate for decimating sigma delta modulation down to four times the Nyquist rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Windowed sinc-in-time (brick-wall in frequency) filters: Although the sinc function's infinite support prevents it from being realizable in finite time, the sinc function can instead be windowed to realize finite impulse response filters.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This approximated filter design, while maintaining *almost no* attenuation of the lower-frequency band of interest, still removes *almost all* undesired high-frequency noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The downside is poor performance in the time domain (e.g. step response overshoot and ripple), higher delay (i.e. their convolution time is inversely proportional to their cutoff transition steepness), and higher computational requirements.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] They are the de facto standard for high fidelity digital audio converters.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Most commercial ΔΣ modulators use integrators as the loop filter, because, as low-pass filters, they push quantization noise up in frequency, which is useful for baseband signals.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] But a ΔΣ modulator's filter does not necessarily need to be a low-pass filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] If a band-pass filter is used instead, then quantization noise is moved up and down in frequency away from the filter's pass-band, so a subsequent pass-band decimation filter will result in a ΔΣ ADC with a bandpass characteristic.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] When a signal is quantized, the resulting signal can be approximated by the addition of white noise with approximately equal intensity across the entire spectrum.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In reality, the quantization noise is, of course, not independent of the signal and this dependence results in limit cycles and is the source of idle tones and pattern noise in delta-sigma converters.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] However, adding dithering noise (Figure 3) reduces such distortion by making quantization noise more random.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] ΔΣ ADCs reduce the amount of this noise in the baseband by spreading it out and shaping it so it is mostly in higher frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It can then be easily filtered out with inexpensive digital filters, without high-precision analog circuits needed by Nyquist ADCs.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] where $f_{\mathrm {s} }$ is the sampling frequency and $2f_{0}$ is the Nyquist rate (the minimum sampling rate needed to avoid aliasing, which is twice the original signal's maximum frequency $f_{0}$ ).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Since oversampling is typically done in powers of two, d represents how many times OSR is doubled.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] As illustrated in Figure 4, the total amount of quantization noise is the same both in a Nyquist converter (yellow + green areas) and in an oversampling converter (blue + green areas).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] But oversampling converters distribute that noise over a much wider frequency range.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The benefit is that the total amount of noise in the frequency band of interest is dramatically smaller for oversampling converters (just the small green area), than for a Nyquist converter (yellow + green total area).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 4 shows how ΔΣ modulation shapes noise to further reduce the amount of quantization noise in the baseband in exchange for increasing noise at higher frequencies (where it can be easily filtered out).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The curves of higher-order ΔΣ modulators achieve even greater reduction of noise in the baseband.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] These curves are derived using mathematical tools called the Laplace transform (for continuous-time signals, e.g., in an ADC's modulation loop) or the Z-transform (for discrete-time signals, e.g. in a DAC's modulation loop).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] These transforms are useful for converting harder math from the time domain into simpler math in the complex frequency domain of the complex variable ${\text{s}}=\sigma +j\omega$ (in the Laplace domain) or ${\text{z}}=Ae^{j\phi }$ (in the z-domain).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The Laplace transform of integration of a function of time corresponds to simply multiplication by ${\tfrac {1}{\text{s}}}$ in Laplace notation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The integrator is assumed to be an ideal integrator to keep the math simple, but a real integrator (or similar filter) may have a more complicated expression.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The process of quantization is approximated as addition with a quantization error noise source.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The noise is often assumed to be white and independent of the signal, though as quantization (signal processing) § Additive noise model explains, that is not always a valid assumption (particularly for low-bit quantization).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This transfer function has a single pole at ${\text{s}}={\text{-1}}$ in the complex plane, so it effectively acts as a first-order low-pass filter on the input signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] (Note: its cutoff frequency could be adjusted as desired by including multiplication by a constant in the loop).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This transfer function has a single zero at ${\text{s}}=0$ and a single pole at ${\text{s}}={\text{-1}},$ so the system effectively acts as a high-pass filter on the noise that starts at 0 at DC, then gradually rises until it reaches the cutoff frequency, and then levels off.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The synchronous ΔΣ DAC's modulation loop (Figure 6), meanwhile, is in discrete-time and so its analysis is in the z-domain.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It is very similar to the above analysis in the Laplace domain and produces similar curves.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Note: many sources§6.1 also analyzes a ΔΣ ADC's modulation loop in the z-domain, which implicitly treats the continuous analog input as a discrete-time signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This may be a valid approximation provided that the input signal is already bandlimited and can be assumed to be not changing on time scales higher than the sampling rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It is particularly appropriate when the modulator is implemented as a switched capacitor circuit, which works by transferring charge between capacitors in clocked time steps.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Its transfer function ${\tfrac {1}{1-{\text{z}}^{\text{-1}}}}$ is often used to label integrators in block diagrams.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In a ΔΣ DAC, the quantizer may be called a *requantizer* or a *digital-to-digital converter* (DDC), because its input is already digital and quantized but is simply reducing from a higher bit depth to a lower bit depth digital signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This is represented in the z-domain by another ${\text{z}}^{\text{-1}}$ delay stage in series with adding quantization noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The noise term's multiplication by $(1-{\text{z}}^{\text{-1}})$ represents a *first difference backward* filter (which has a single pole at the origin and a single zero at ${\text{z}}{=}1$ ) and thus high-pass filters the noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] For comparison, oversampling a Nyquist ADC (without any noise shaping) only improves its ENOB by ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ bits for every doubling of the OSR, which is only 1⁄3 of the ENOB growth rate of a first-order ΔΣM.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In practice, circuits inevitably experience other noise sources that limit resolution, making the higher-resolution cells impractical.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Assuming quantization were homogeneous (e.g., if it were linear), that integrator can be moved from the demodulator to instead be on the input signal, before the summation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The linearity property of integration, ${\textstyle \int a+\int b=\int (a+b),}$ allows the two integrators to be combined, so a delta-sigma modulator and demodulator is obtained.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] But because the quantizer is *not* homogeneous, the above is not a sufficient derivation of their hypothetical equivalence, so while delta-sigma is *inspired* by delta modulation, the two are distinct in operation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] From the first block diagram in Figure 7, the integrator in the feedback path can be removed if the feedback is taken directly from the input of the low-pass filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In other words, doing delta-sigma modulation instead of delta modulation has effectively swapped the ordering of the integrator and quantizer operations.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The net effect is a simpler implementation that has the profound added benefit of shaping the quantization noise to be mostly in frequencies above the signals of interest.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This effect becomes more dramatic with increased oversampling, which allows for quantization noise to be somewhat programmable.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] On the other hand, delta modulation shapes both noise and signal equally.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Additionally, the quantizer (e.g., comparator) used in delta modulation has a small output representing a small step up and down the quantized approximation of the input while the quantizer used in delta-sigma must take values *outside* of the range of the input signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 8a: Schematic of a simple delta-sigma converter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Figure 8b: Simulated scope view of key voltage signals over time.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Each minor vertical division is 1 μs, which corresponds to a sampling event of the 1 MHz clock.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The circuit below focuses on a simple first-order, two-level quantization synchronous delta-sigma ADC without decimation.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] To ease understanding, a simple circuit schematic (Figure 8a) using ideal elements is simulated (Figure 8b voltages).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The 20 kHz input sine wave **s(t)** is converted to a 1-bit PDM digital result **Q(t)**.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] 20 kHz is used as an example because that is considered the upper limit of human hearing.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This circuit can be laid out on a breadboard with inexpensive discrete components (note some variations use different biasing and use simpler RC low-pass filters for integration instead of op amps).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] For simplicity, the D flip-flop is powered by dual supply voltages of VDD = +1 V and VSS = -1 V, so its binary output **Q(t)** is either +1 V or -1 V.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The 2-input inverting op amp integrator combines **s(t)** with **Q(t)** to produce **Ɛ(t)**: $\varepsilon (t)=-{\frac {1}{RC}}\int (s(t)+Q(t))dt.$ The Greek letter epsilon is used because **Ɛ(t)** contains the accumulated error that is repeatedly corrected by the feedback mechanism.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] While both its inputs **s(t)** and **Q(t)** vary between -1 and 1 volts, **Ɛ(t)** instead only varies by a couple *millivolts* about 0 V.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Because of the integrator's *negative* sign, when **Ɛ(t)** next gets sampled to produce **Q(t)**, the +**Q(t)** in this integral actually represents *negative* feedback from the previous clock cycle.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] An ideal D flip-flop samples **Ɛ(t)** at the clock rate of 1 MHz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The scope view (Figure 8b) has a minor division equal to the sampling period of 1 μs, so every minor division corresponds to a sampling event.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Since the flip-flop is assumed to be ideal, it treats any input voltage greater than 0 V as logical high and any input voltage smaller than 0 V as logical low, no matter how close it is to 0 V (ignoring issues of sample-and-hold time violations and metastability).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The rightmost integrator performs digital-to-analog conversion on **Q(t)** to produce a demodulated analog output **r(t)**, which reconstructs the original sine wave input as piece-wise linear diagonal segments.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Although **r(t)** appears coarse at this 50x oversampling rate, **r(t)** can be low-pass filtered to isolate the original signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] As the sampling rate is increased relative to the input signal's maximum frequency, **r(t)** will more closely approximate the original input **s(t)**.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It is worth noting that if no decimation ever took place, the digital representation from a 1-bit delta-sigma modulator is simply a PDM signal, which can easily be converted to analog using a low-pass filter, as simple as a resistor and capacitor.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] However, in general, a delta-sigma DAC converts a discrete time series signal of digital samples at a high bit depth into a low-bit-depth (often 1-bit) signal, usually at a much higher sampling rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] As the discrete Fourier transform and discrete-time Fourier transform articles explain, a periodically sampled signal inherently contains multiple higher frequency copies or *images* of the signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] It is often desirable to remove these higher-frequency images prior to performing the actual delta-sigma modulation stage, in order to ease requirements on the eventual analog low-pass filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This can be done by upsampling using an interpolation filter and is often the first step prior to performing delta-sigma modulation in DACs.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] This simple first-order modulation can be improved by cascading two or more overflowing accumulators, each of which is equivalent to a first-order delta-sigma modulator.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The resulting multi-stage noise shaping (MASH) structure has a steeper noise shaping property, so is commonly used in digital audio.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The carry outputs are combined through summations and delays to produce a binary output, the width of which depends on the number of stages (order) of the MASH.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The technique was first presented in the early 1960s by professor Yasuhiko Yasuda while he was a student at the University of Tokyo.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] The name *delta-sigma* comes directly from the presence of a delta modulator and an integrator, as firstly introduced by Inose et al. in their patent application.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] That is, the name comes from integrating or *summing* **differences**, which, in mathematics, are operations usually associated with Greek letters sigma and delta respectively.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Both names *sigma-delta* and *delta-sigma* are frequently used.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Kikkert and Miller published a continuous-time variant called Asynchronous Delta Sigma Modulation (ADSM or ASDM) in 1975, which uses either a Schmitt trigger (i.e. a comparator with hysteresis) or (as the paper argues is equivalent) a comparator with fixed delay.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] In the example in Figure 9, when the integral of the error exceeds its limits, the output changes state, producing a pulse-width modulated (PWM) output wave.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] Amplitude information is converted, without quantization noise, into time information of the output PWM.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/delta-sigma-modulation] To convert this continuous time PWM to discrete time, the PWM may be sampled by a time-to-digital converter, whose limited resolution adds noise which can be shaped by feeding it back.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Any feedback loop functions as a filter.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Noise shaping works by putting quantization noise in a feedback loop designed to filter the noise as desired.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] In this model, when any sample's bit depth is reduced, the quantization error is measured and on the next cycle added with the next sample prior to quantization.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The effect is that the quantization error is low-pass filtered by a 2-sample boxcar filter (also known as a simple moving average filter).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] As a result, compared to before, the quantization error has lower power at higher frequencies and higher power at lower frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The filter's cutoff frequency can be adjusted by modifying b, the proportion of error from the previous sample that is fed back.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] More generally, any FIR filter or IIR filter can be used to create a more complex frequency response curve.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Such filters can be designed using the weighted least squares method.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] In the case of digital audio, typically the weighting function used is one divided by the absolute threshold of hearing curve, i.e.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Adding an appropriate amount of dither during quantization prevents determinable errors correlated to the signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] If dither is not used, then noise shaping effectively functions merely as distortion shaping — pushing the distortion energy around to different frequency bands, but it is still distortion.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] then the quantization error truly becomes noise, and the process indeed yields noise shaping.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Noise shaping in audio is most commonly applied as a bit-reduction scheme.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The most basic form of dither is flat, white noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The ear, however, is less sensitive to certain frequencies than others at low levels (see Equal-loudness contour).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] By using noise shaping, the quantization error can be effectively spread around so that more of it is focused on frequencies that can't be heard as well and less of it is focused on frequencies that can.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The result is that where the ear is most critical, the quantization error can be reduced greatly and where the ear is less sensitive, the noise is much greater.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] This can give a perceived noise reduction of 4 bits compared to straight dither.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] So, although 16-bit samples only have 96 dB of dynamic range across the entire spectrum (see quantization distortion calculations), noise-shaped dithering can, however, increase the perceived audio dynamic range to 120 dB.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Since around 1989, 1-bit delta-sigma modulators have been used in analog-to-digital converters.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] This involves sampling the audio at a very high rate (2.8224 million samples per second, for example) but only using a single bit.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Because only 1 bit is used, this converter only has 6.02 dB of dynamic range.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The noise floor, however, is spread throughout the entire non-aliased frequency range below the Nyquist frequency of 1.4112 MHz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Noise shaping is used to lower the noise present in the audible range (20 Hz to 20 kHz) and increase the noise above the audible range.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] This results in a broadband dynamic range of only 7.78 dB, but it is not consistent among frequency bands, and in the lowest frequencies (the audible range) the dynamic range is much greater — over 100 dB.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Noise shaping is inherently built into the delta-sigma modulators.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] The 1-bit converter is the basis of the DSD format by Sony.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Most A/D converters made since 2000 use multi-bit or multi-level delta-sigma modulators that yield more than 1 bit output so that proper dither can be added in the feedback loop.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] For traditional PCM sampling the signal is then decimated to 44.1 kHz or other appropriate sample rates.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] Analog Devices uses what they refer to as "Noise Shaping Requantizer", and Texas Instruments uses what they refer to as "SNRBoost" to lower the noise floor approximately 30db compared to the surrounding frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] This comes at a cost of non-continuous operation but produces a nice bathtub shape to the spectrum floor.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/noise-shaping] This can be combined with other techniques to further enhance the resolution of the spectrum.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] In signal processing, **oversampling** is the process of sampling a signal at a sampling frequency significantly higher than the Nyquist rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Theoretically, a bandwidth-limited signal can be perfectly reconstructed if sampled at the Nyquist rate or above it.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] The Nyquist rate is defined as twice the bandwidth of the signal.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Oversampling is capable of improving resolution and signal-to-noise ratio, and can be helpful in avoiding aliasing and phase distortion by relaxing anti-aliasing filter performance requirements.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] A signal is said to be oversampled by a factor of *N* if it is sampled at *N* times the Nyquist rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] There are three main reasons for performing oversampling: to improve anti-aliasing performance, to increase resolution and to reduce noise.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Oversampling can make it easier to realize analog anti-aliasing filters.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Without oversampling, it is very difficult to implement filters with the sharp cutoff necessary to maximize use of the available bandwidth without exceeding the Nyquist limit.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] By increasing the bandwidth of the sampling system, design constraints for the anti-aliasing filter may be relaxed.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Once sampled, the signal can be digitally filtered and downsampled to the desired sampling frequency.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] In modern integrated circuit technology, the digital filter associated with this downsampling is easier to implement than a comparable analog filter required by a non-oversampled system.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] In practice, oversampling is implemented in order to reduce cost and improve performance of an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) or digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] When oversampling by a factor of N, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) increases by ${\sqrt {N}}$ , because summing up uncorrelated noise increases its amplitude by ${\sqrt {N}}$ , while summing up a coherent signal increases its average by N.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] For instance, to implement a 24-bit converter, it is sufficient to use a 20-bit converter that can run at 256 times the target sampling rate.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Combining 256 consecutive 20-bit samples can increase the SNR by a factor of 16, effectively adding 4 bits to the resolution and producing a single sample with 24-bit resolution.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] This averaging is only effective if the signal contains sufficient uncorrelated noise to be recorded by the ADC.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] If not, in the case of a stationary input signal, all $2^{n}$ samples would have the same value and the resulting average would be identical to this value; so in this case, oversampling would have made no improvement.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] In similar cases where the ADC records no noise and the input signal is changing over time, oversampling improves the result, but to an inconsistent and unpredictable extent.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Adding some dithering noise to the input signal can actually improve the final result because the dither noise allows oversampling to work to improve resolution.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] In many practical applications, a small increase in noise is well worth a substantial increase in measurement resolution.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] If multiple samples are taken of the same quantity with uncorrelated noise added to each sample, then because, as discussed above, uncorrelated signals combine more weakly than correlated ones, averaging *N* samples reduces the noise power by a factor of *N*.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] If, for example, we oversample by a factor of 4, the signal-to-noise ratio in terms of power improves by a factor of four, which corresponds to a factor of two improvement in terms of voltage.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Certain kinds of ADCs known as delta-sigma converters produce disproportionately more quantization noise at higher frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] By running these converters at some multiple of the target sampling rate, and low-pass filtering the oversampled signal down to half the target sampling rate, a final result with *less* noise (over the entire band of the converter) can be obtained.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Delta-sigma converters use a technique called noise shaping to move the quantization noise to the higher frequencies.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Consider a signal with a bandwidth or highest frequency of *B* = 100 Hz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] The sampling theorem states that sampling frequency would have to be greater than 200 Hz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Sampling at four times that rate requires a sampling frequency of 800 Hz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] This gives the anti-aliasing filter a transition band of 300 Hz ((*f*s/2) − *B* = (800 Hz/2) − 100 Hz = 300 Hz) instead of 0 Hz if the sampling frequency was 200 Hz.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Achieving an anti-aliasing filter with 0 Hz transition band is unrealistic, whereas an anti-aliasing filter with a transition band of 300 Hz is not difficult.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] The term oversampling is also used to denote a process used in the reconstruction phase of digital-to-analog conversion, in which an intermediate high sampling rate is used between the digital input and the analog output.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Here, digital interpolation is used to add additional samples between recorded samples, thereby converting the data to a higher sample rate, a form of upsampling.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] When the resulting higher-rate samples are converted to analog, a less complex and less expensive analog reconstruction filter is required.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Essentially, this is a way to shift some of the complexity of reconstruction from analog to the digital domain.
[src:sigma-delta-adc/oversampling] Oversampling in the ADC can achieve some of the same benefits as using a higher sample rate at the DAC.
